<TEXT>
most newspapers aim to serve their readers but 
street news is unlike most newspapers its mission is to serve its 
salespeople an army of homeless men and women 
each day editor in chief hutchinson persons deploys a ragtag 
sales force from his times square offices some arrive hungry on 
their first day and are given a sandwich and 10 papers which sell 
for 75 cents each 
of that 50 cents goes into the salesmans pocket and a nickel 
goes into a bank account in his or her name money from the account 
can only be withdrawn as a cashiers check made out to a landlord 
for an apartment 
if you can shake a cup you can sell this newspaper says 
persons a 33yearold rock musician who has been active in 
philanthropic efforts were trying to offer an alternative to 
panhandling 
the monthly street news is just 2 issues old but persons says 
it is a success the first issue sold 40000 copies in new york 
the second issue debuted in los angeles and denver within 18 
months persons expects street news will be available in at least 
16 cities with total sales reaching a million 
the first issue featured articles by singers gloria estefan 
richie havens joe cocker james taylor and actor danny aiello 
there were stories about the art of train conversation and 
tourist in tiananmen 
the second issue featured stories by joe simmons of the rap 
group rundmc and actress mariette hartley but the emphasis was 
on articles by and about the homeless themselves including a 
feature about one of the newspapers top salesmen who also wrote a 
story about loneliness 
in the premiere issue persons wrote that he was inspired to 
create the newspaper when he saw homeless people in grand central 
terminal 
i thought what an untapped work force all these people just 
lying around here but what can they do this thought plagued me 
off and on day and night for about a week until suddenly it hit 
me they could sell newspapers persons wrote 
for money and help he turned to connections he had made as a 
musician and in his work on live aid and as head of street aid a 
nonprofit organization that fights hunger in america 
homelessness has gotten to be a such a crisis that everyone 
has trouble giving to someone with a cup said wendy koltun the 
papers advertising director and a former dancer with the new york 
city ballet 
when they hear of someone working for a living they feel 
better giving them money its not like youre giving them a free 
meal 
some of the 150 salespeople who joined the staff have dropped 
out but half remain persons estimates they make an average of 
200 a week one man sold 1100 copies in four days for 550 in 
cash and 55 in the bank 
william allen 36 said he was on the verge of homelessness 
after losing his job three months ago but the newspaper gave him a 
way to try to raise enough rent money to stay off the streets 
im going to get my life back together he said 
jesse aki windley 46 netted 300 one week the college 
graduate said the breakup of his marriage sent him into a tailspin 
that ended on the streets now the paper that bills itself as 
americas motivational nonprofit newspaper has resurrected his 
hopes 
my aim is to be the director of distribution he said 
others have more modest goals bobby gaddy 47 and homeless for 
three months sells 25 to 30 papers a day its enough to buy food 
and cigarettes but not enough to keep a roof over his head ill 
be down in the subways somewhere who knows where ill sleep he 
said 
the newspaper promotes opportunities in its classified ads one 
tells where to redeem bottles and cans another job requires 
residence or referral letter from shelter or regularly attended 
kitchen 
but windley says he hopes never to leave street news 
i intend to be here until the building disintegrates he 
said i feel as though im part of the company i feel im one of 
the cinderblocks i have friends here why do i want to stay im 
at home 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

