<TEXT>
the soviet union is packing up mig23 fighter 
jets based at vietnams cam ranh bay the usbuilt port the 
soviets turned into their largest naval facility outside their 
borders administration sources say 
there have been a series of reports that they have been 
disassembling and packing up their mig23s for shipment said one 
source who spoke on condition he not be identified by name 
the reports have triggered speculation the soviets might be 
scaling down or could be preparing a pullout from cam ranh bay 
the changes indicate it could be a complete pullout or it 
could lead to a significant reduction in soviet military 
involvement at the base the source said thursday 
there could be several reasons behind such a possible pullback 
the source and other asian specialists said in a series of 
interviews 
the move could be a reflection of the worldwide soviet reduction 
in naval activities that has occurred over the past months which 
some us analysts have speculated may be due to economic pressures 
the cam ranh changes also could foreshadow a possible unilateral 
soviet initiative designed to oneup the united states as it 
prepares to enter into negotiations on renewing leases for us 
bases in the philippines the administration source said 
it could be a setup to embarrass us the source said 
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev proposed several years ago to 
withdraw from the base his most strategic foreign site in asia 
if the united states would pull out of the six bases it has leased 
in the philippines 
us officials rejected the proposal 
the leases on the us bases expire in 1991 and the renewal has 
become a hotly debated topic particularly in light of the recent 
us intervention against the rebel forces attempting to overthrow 
president corazon aquino 
one defense analyst who declined to comment specifically on the 
mig23 move said the idea of a unilateral soviet drawdown to point 
up the us problems with the philippines wouldnt be out of line 
with pentagon assumptions 
theyd like to complicate our lives the analyst said of the 
soviets weve been predicting some deemphasis there 
jonathan pollack the head of the rand corporations political 
science department and a specialist on the role of the soviet union 
in indochina said the soviets have tended to keep about 20 vessels 
and 40 aircraft at the cam ranh base 
pollack in a telephone interview said he would not be 
surprised by a soviet cutback 
if there are changes in the more distant deployments it could 
be explained by a mix of factors not only economic but also a 
reconsideration of what is crucial to soviet security concerns 
he said 
the analyst said that lots of gorbachevs proposals are for a 
pr public relations effect but he wouldnt be surprised if a 
reduction at cam ranh bay was made without any publicity 
in the context of what clearly is a major change in the 
ussoviet relationship the value of distant soviet bases is 
reduced he said 
cam ranh bay located several hundred miles from ho chi minh 
city formerly saigon on vietnams eastern coast offers one of 
the finest harbors in indochina and provides a safe anchorage to 
all types of vessels year round 
the japanese made use of the harbor in world war ii but it was 
transformed into a modern military facility by the united states 
during the vietnam conflict when warehouses airstrips and other 
naval support facilities were built 
according to the londonbased international institute for 
strategic studies the soviet union has regularly deployed at the 
base an average of one or two submarines and a range of surface 
combat ships as well as patrol mine warfare amphibious and 
support vessels 
the air units have included six tu95 bear longrange 
bombers 16 tu16 badger fighter aircraft and a squadron of the 
mig23 flogger fighter jets the institute reported in its 
the military balance 19891990 publication 
