<TEXT>
new irs rules will free employees from having 
to deal with expense accounts on their tax returns 
if the rules are followed to the letter employers will not have 
to withhold taxes from their workers expense allowances 
the new regulations announced thursday by the internal revenue 
service are designed to avoid harsh results for employers who 
have reasonable substantiation methods said mary oppenhiemer 
the agencys deputy assistant chief counsel 
starting in 1990 an employer must require that employees 
substantiate expenses and turn back any portion of an advance that 
is not substantiated if those two conditions are met the employer 
need not list any part of the expense reimbursement as income on 
the workers w2 form and the worker will not have to claim a 
deduction for the allowance 
in that case ms oppenhiemer said the only amounts that will 
ever show up on the employees form w2 are amounts the employee 
does not substantiate or does not return to the employer 
if the worker does not substantiate expenses or does not return 
any overage that excess would be listed as income on the w2 an 
employee then might be able to take an itemized deduction for part 
of the allowance 
the regulations permit employers to rely on a goodfaith 
interpretation of the law in accounting for 1989 expenses 
ms oppenhiemer told reporters the new regulations are in line 
with the agencys moves toward simplification 
we believe that the regulations will not impose any 
significant new administrative burden on most employers she 
said in fact she said the changes will actually reduce 
compliance burdens for many taxpayers 
the regulations also require that taxes be withheld from expense 
allowances unless the substantiation and returnofexcess 
procedures are followed current rules say withholding is not 
required if the employer reasonably believes the allowances will be 
used for business expenses 
the tougher withholding rule will take effect july 1 
the irs also announced that the standard mileage rate for 
business use of an automobile in 1990 will be 26 cents a mile up 
from 25 cents this year 
this marks the first time the irs has disclosed this annual 
adjustment in advance the rate for a year is usually announced 
about two months before the end of that year 
for 1990 and later years the business mileage rate will be 26 
cents across the board present rules permit the full rate only for 
the first 15000 miles and 11 cents for each additional mile 
the irs said employers will be deemed to have met substantiation 
requirements if they use the 26cent rate in reimbursing employees 
for business use of their cars 
the standard mileage rate for use of a personal car for 
charitable activities will continue at 12 cents a mile next year 
the rate for purposes of calculating medical and moving expenses 
will remain at 9 cents a mile 
another new procedure announced thursday provides a simplified 
safe harbor option for employer reimbursements for employee 
travel expenses 
this will allow employers to use a rate of 122 per day for 28 
highcost areas and 85 per day for all other parts of the united 
states 
the highcost areas death valley los angeles palm springs 
san francisco and santa barbara calif aspen and vail colo the 
washington dc area atlanta chicago annapolis columbia and 
ocean city md andover boston marthas vineyardnantucket and 
plymouth mass conway nh 
atlantic city newark ocean citycape may and 
princetontrenton nj new york city and white plains ny 
philadelphia newport ri hilton head sc and dallasfort 
worth 
