<TEXT>
government scientists say there is no quick 
solution to the problem of brucellosis spreading from wild bison 
and elk into cattle herds bordering yellowstone national park 
a twoday meeting of scientists and others from the departments 
of agriculture and interior was held here this week but two senior 
officials said in a joint interview thursday that no one is close 
to a decision on how to deal with the problem 
brucellosis of cattle has also been called bangs disease and 
infectious abortion it can cause undulant fever in humans usually 
through unpasteurized milk or direct contact with infected animals 
the agriculture department in cooperation with state and local 
governments livestock associations and animal health groups has 
been striving for decades to eliminate the disease from commercial 
herds 
so far according to usda officials 27 states are free of 
brucellosis most of the remainder are in the south 
the problem with bison or american buffalo and elk in the huge 
yellowstone national park is that infected animals can roam onto 
cattle rangelands mingle with herds and thus spread the disease 
while were talking about a very small number of cattle and 
bison and elk in the yellowstone area the potential threat can 
extend over a much wider area said john dennis of the national 
park service 
cattle of course greatly outnumber bison in the united states 
there are nearly 100 million head of cattle compared with an 
estimated 500000 bison including public and private herds 
yellowstone has around 2000 head 
but prospective buyers and shippers of breeding cattle can be 
highly wary of animals from known areas of brucellosis infection 
that is true on the growing international market for livestock as 
well as domestically dennis said 
its a lot easier to do that interchange if everybody is in 
the same status on brucellosis he said some countries may not 
even accept cattle from the united states if we have pockets of 
brucellosis 
john kopec of usdas animal and plant health inspection service 
said that there is much to learn about brucellosis in yellowstone 
we dont know absolutely that this disease may have come from 
infected elk and in one case maybe some bison running around 
he said we dont know this unequivocally but we have more or 
less ruled out all the other sources 
kopec said that since the early 1960s there have six outbreaks 
of brucellosis among cattle in the yellowstone area in which 
infection from other cattle has been ruled out the most recent was 
in february after the disease was detected in an idaho packing 
plant and the slaughtered animal traced to wyoming 
the owner of the exposed cattle decided to liquidate the herd 
sending older cattle to slaughter and younger animals to a 
quarantined feedlot and subsequently to slaughter 
kopec said that one of the problems in the yellowstone area is 
that we havent unequivocally answered the question whether 
bison and elk in the park have carried the disease over many 
centuries or whether it is more recent 
meanwhile he said the cattle industry is putting pressure on 
federal and state authorities to help safeguard commercial herds 
against the potential threat of brucellosis from wild creatures 
kopec and dennis said more experiments and study are needed the 
answers will come slowly 
we may be talking years kopec said its not something 
that will be done overnight 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department says the soviet 
union has bought 410000 metric tons of us wheat at subsidized 
prices for delivery in 198990 the seventh year of a longterm 
grain supply agreement 
f paul dickerson general sales manager for the departments 
foreign agricultural service said thursday that shipments are 
scheduled in january and february 
the wheat was sold under the departments export enhancement 
program or eep which provides subsidies to exporters selling us 
commodities to designated foreign markets 
dickerson said only 14200 tons of wheat remain in the soviet 
unions current eep allocation of 15 million tons announced may 2 
it was the second us wheat sale since the seventh year of the 
longterm grain agreement began oct 1 although more than 103 
million tons of corn have been sold for 198990 delivery along 
with soybeans and soybean meal a sale of 215000 tons was reported 
monday 
the pact runs through dec 31 1990 and a new agreement is 
being negotiated 
in 198889 the sixth year of the current agreement the soviet 
union bought about 54 million tons of wheat and more than 163 
million tons of corn plus soybeans soybean meal and grain 
sorghums 
a metric ton is 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels of 
wheat the 410000 tons are equal to more than 15 million bushels 
worth about 57 million at recent us farm prices 
dickerson reported the subsidies at an average of 1681 per 
ton or about 46 cents per bushel 
the eep arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and 
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced 
prices to meet foreign competition the exporters then collect free 
government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses or 
subsidies 
dickerson said the wheat was sold by alfred c toepfer 
international inc 150000 tons louis dreyfus corp 135000 
cargill inc 50000 continental grain co 25000 j aron amp co 
25000 and mitsubishi international corp 25000 
