<TEXT>
the unemployment rate edged up from 53 
percent to 54 percent in november even though the economy added 
210000 new jobs and manufacturing employment fell for the eighth 
consecutive month the government said today 
the labor department report showed job growth last month was far 
greater than most analysts expected but the government also 
revised downward sharply the number of new nonfarm jobs created in 
october from 233000 to 93000 
the civilian unemployment rate climbed 01 percentage point as 
more than 67 million americans were looking for jobs but unable to 
find them that data comes from the departments household survey 
which also showed that 1177 million people held jobs in the 
civilian economy 
the stock market reacted favorably to the report taking the 
evidence of sluggish growth as a sign the federal reserve board 
would move to further relax its credit policy and thus lower 
interest rates 
analysts however were split on whether or when such a 
reduction would come and at odds as well over whether the economy 
was on the verge of recession 
i dont think these numbers suggest further easing said 
washington economist michael evans the economy is moving along 
in second gear its not very weak and its not very strong 
but allen sinai chief economist for boston co economic 
advisers said the manufacturing sector was clearly in a recession 
and appeared to be having a spillover effect on certain services 
industries that could bring a full recession 
i think this is it sinai said this economy is at or near 
some sort of recession he predicted the fed would reduce 
interest rates but said it was unclear whether the central bank 
would move immediately or wait until its yearend meeting in 10 
days 
the manufacturing slump has contributed to the overall slowdown 
in the economy as the year draws to a close and todays report 
provided further evidence that the sectors lackluster performance 
continues 
the average manufacturing work week fell from 408 to 407 hours 
and overtime was unchanged at an average of 37 hours a week 
the department said the dramatic revision of octobers job 
growth number resulted from overestimating new hiring in state and 
local educational institutions which is difficult to measure as 
the school year begins 
with that revision taken into account the government said the 
average monthtomonth gain in jobs during the second half of 1989 
has been about 160000 well below the average monthly gain of 
270000 posted in the past 2 years 
virtually all of the growth in the past year has been in the 
service sector and november was no exception 
wholesale and retail trade posted job gains of 18000 and 
33000 respectively last month and business and health services 
also reported significant payroll expansions 
but the outlook in the goodsproducing sector particularly 
manufacturing was not as good 
mining and construction reported modest employment gains last 
month adding 7000 and 17000 positions respectively 
exacerbating the decline in manufacturing was another bad month 
for automobile manufacturing which reported a decline of 15000 
jobs in november after losing 10000 from september to october 
that decline caused overall employment in the durablegoods 
sector of manufacturing to slip by 24000 jobs last month 
the labor department said manufacturing employment has declined 
by 165000 since march with auto and electrical equipment 
accounting for 100000 of the lost jobs 
analysts had predicted the report would show about 150000 new 
jobs last month and the larger figure would appear to indicate 
that the economy is strong enough that the federal reserve need not 
reduce interest rates further 
the sharp october job revision however and the continued slump 
in manufacturing could give the fed policymakers enough evidence 
that the slowdown has reached a dangerous point and that lower 
interest rates might help spark more robust growth 
the central banks chief concern about easing interest rates 
centers on inflation and todays report contained somewhat 
encouraging news on that front 
average hourly earnings were unchanged in november and average 
weekly earnings declined by 04 percent over the year hourly 
earnings have increased by 36 percent and average weekly earnings 
by 30 percent both of those gains lag well behind consumer 
inflation which has been in the annual range of 45 percent 
the 54 percent civilian jobless rate was the highest since it 
was 54 percent in january for the past six months the rate had 
been either 53 percent or 52 percent 
the rate increased despite the moderately strong addition of 
210000 nonfarm jobs because the labor force those with jobs or 
actively seeking them expanded by 410000 people last month after 
growing by just 65000 from september to october 
the unemployment rates among major demographic groups changed 
little for the most part in november although joblessness for all 
teenagers shot up from 149 percent to 155 percent 
the rates among other groups were 
adult white men 40 percent up from 38 percent in october 
adult white women 40 percent unchanged 
white teenagers 112 percent up from 104 percent 
all blacks 121 percent up from 118 percent 
adult black men 107 percent up from 103 percent 
adult black women 104 percent up from 10 percent 
black teenagers 326 percent down from 361 percent 
hispanics 78 percent down from 79 percent 
in a separate calculation of unemployment that counts members of 
the armed forces stationed in the united states the labor 
department said the november unemployment rate was 53 percent up 
from 52 percent in october 
</TEXT>
