<TEXT>
susy thomas is closer than ever to realizing a 
dream she has held through five children and 11 years of training 
that involved 40mile commutes to class 
the 37yearold member of the navajo tribe near tohatchi nm 
wants to join the small number of navajos trained to teach in us 
schools 
i want to teach elementary education because among native 
americans early childhood education is important mrs thomas 
said during an interview after being named by the national council 
of teachers of english as the groups first presidential scholar 
i want to let them know they are native americans and they 
have a big world to conquer she added 
mrs thomas of the red running into the water people clan 
was awarded 1000 to help her complete her parttime studies in 
1991 at the university of new mexico gallup nm 
she currently is taking courses in art history and education 
foundation at a university branch near home she plans to save the 
1000 check until the fall when she will make her final push to 
complete about 22 hours 
the softspoken woman accepted the award during the councils 
annual convention in baltimore wearing a native blackandred satin 
dress silverchain belt and boots standing on stage with her were 
14 youngsters from the chuska school where she is a speech therapy 
assistant 
chuska school is an elementary boarding school for indian 
children who live in the rugged country of the navajo reservation 
the bureau of indian affairs says just 41 percent of its 1039 
teachers were indians in 1987 chuska school principal helen 
zongolowicz said few indians are trained to teach in us schools 
mainly because of the small size of the minority group and the high 
dropout rate 
among navajos the dropout rate in elementary and secondary 
school is about 30 percent with a higher percentage for college 
students 
my husband is very supportive of the idea of my getting my 
degree and going into teaching said mrs thomas hes a 
counselor himself working with children in kindergarten through 
the third grade these are the years to really work with them get 
them to use their mind and set their goals their minds are very 
delicate 
when she was an elementary student mrs thomas recalled we 
were punished if we were caught talking in navajo she said many 
of her friends eventually dropped out because of the negative 
attitudes about language and indian culture 
mrs thomas said she refused to give up because i was the 
oldest in the family i gave some of what i learned to my younger 
brothers and they looked up to me my parents praised me and i 
had no choice i had to become the interpreter for the family 
the idea of teaching young children first came when mrs thomas 
was in the eighth grade and second and thirdgrade teachers 
would have us work with them 
to attend high school she said we traveled 50 miles one way 
each day about an hour on the bus mrs thomas is the first 
woman in her family to complete high school she married shortly 
after graduating and focused on raising a family her husband 
returned to school to earn a degree in counseling 
mrs thomas worked for a time as a substitute teachers aide 
the principal there was telling me you should go back to school 
and take classes in the evening she said 
eventually despite her growing family she began working toward 
an associate degree in speech pathology shifting later to special 
education and holding jobs in that field before deciding she 
wanted the broader focus of teaching language arts in the primary 
grades 
a lot of couples go to school together and get degrees said 
mrs thomas referring to younger navajo adults but it has been 
a struggle going to school course by course all of this time 
she has to travel 40 miles one way for classes on the gallup 
campus 
a staff development course two summers ago at the chuska school 
sparked mrs thomas desire to become an elementary language arts 
teacher with its emphasis on writing and reading about topics 
linked to students own lives a whole language approach works 
well in involving indian youngsters in school learning she said 
in the whole language approach we use things from the 
childrens own environment and everyday activities at home and we 
see more achievement she said 
we were punished but now its praise and positive 
reinforcement she said i think of all these people on the 
reservation out of school on the street learning would have 
meant more to them they got lost 
i know children in elementary school today will succeed i 
look at their work hanging in the hallways its amazing to compare 
it with what our teachers had us do when i was a child 
