<TEXT>
some financially troubled borrowers who 
cheated the farmers home administration avoided foreclosure by 
taking advantage of debt settlement measures intended for borrowers 
who acted in good faith officials say 
the fmha estimates 330 badfaith borrowers paid off their debt 
or bought back foreclosed farms through provisions in the 1987 
agricultural credit act 
sen kent conrad dnd has sponsored a senateapproved bill 
to limit the debtrestructuring program to farmers who acted 
properly 
a general accounting office fact sheet given to conrad last week 
lists examples of eight borrowers in one unspecified county office 
who benefited from the program despite cheating fmha by selling 
collateral hiding income or paying other creditors more than 
necessary 
one farmer who is eligible for the program had 91284 in his 
checking account while he was 76269 past due on fmha loans 
were not talking about a big thing but obviously we dont 
want those who acted in bad faith to get the benefits of the 
legislation and that was clearly congress intent when they passed 
the agricultural credit act said conrad chairman of the 
senates agricultural credit subcommittee 
fmha would actually lose some money by foreclosing on those 
borrowers but the agency estimates a net savings of 10 million 
because other farmers would be discouraged from cheating conrad 
said 
i think it is really an issue of assuring taxpayers that the 
system is going to operate in a way that assures that those who 
havent operated in good faith dont get the benefits of the 
agricultural credit act conrad said 
the senate passed conrads bill shortly before congress 
adjourned last month the house has taken no action on the measure 
which is backed by fmha 
we are in favor of anything that will enable us to collect 
reasonable debts on a reasonable basis that conrads bill is a 
step in the right direction agriculture department spokesman 
john kislak said thursday 
fmha is often called the governments farm lender of last resort 
because loans are made only to those who cannot qualify at banks or 
other commercial sources 
with loan delinquencies rising in 1987 congress forced fmha to 
write down loans or spread out payments whenever that would cost 
the government less than foreclosure 
badfaith borrowers have taken advantage of a provision under 
which farmers who dont qualify for restructuring can buy out of 
their debt at the adjusted value of their collateral according to 
the gao report 
in one location borrowers who engaged in multiple instances 
of bad faith bought out their loans that way the gao said 
another provision badfaith borrowers have used gives them the 
option to purchase or lease land the fmha took from them in 
foreclosure 
